SIMPLE: gyration
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gyration
<hw>Gy*ra"tion</hw> <pr>(j⟦isl⟧*r⟦amac⟧"sh⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of turning or whirling, as around a fixed
center; a circular or spiral motion; motion about an axis; rotation;
revolution.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>gyrations</qex> of an ascending balloon.</q> <rj><qau>De
Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If a burning coal be nimbly moved round in a circle, with
<qex>gyrations</qex> continually repeated, the whole circle will appear
like fire.</q> <rj><qau>Sir I. Newton. </qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the whorls of a spiral
univalve shell.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Center of gyration</b></col>. <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <cd>See
under <er>Center</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Radius of gyration</b></col>,
<cd>the distance between the axis of a rotating body and its center of
gyration.</cd> <au>Rankine.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gyratory</ent>⟦br⟧
